ionMs,\n  cost_usd: ctx.cost ?? null,\n  attempts: null,\n  acResults: contract?.acceptanceCriteria ? ... : null,\n  filesChanged: contract?.changedFiles ? [...contract.changedFiles] : [],\n  testResults: contract?.testResults ? ... : null,\n  errors: [],\n};\n```\nTest \"entry contains all required fields with correct types\" (line 66) verifies all fields exist with correct types. 19/19 tests pass.\n\n---\n\n## AC 3: Null/missing fields set to null\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// telemetry-writer.test.ts lines 125-135\nit('unavailable fields are null when no output contract', async () => {\n  const ctx = makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir, outputContract: null });\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(ctx);\n  const entry: TelemetryEntry = JSON.parse(readTelemetryFile(tmpDir).trim());\n  expect(entry.attempts).toBeNull();\n  expect(entry.acResults).toBeNull();\n  expect(entry.testResults).toBeNull();\n  expect(entry.filesChanged).toEqual([]);\n  expect(entry.errors).toEqual([]);\n});\n```\nTest passes. When `outputContract` is null, `attempts`, `acResults`, `testResults` are all `null`.\n\n---\n\n## AC 4: appendFileSync used (not truncate) and .codeharness dir created\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// src/lib/telemetry-writer.ts lines 106-108\nconst dir = join(ctx.projectDir, TELEMETRY_DIR);\nmkdirSync(dir, { recursive: true });\nappendFileSync(join(dir, TELEMETRY_FILE), JSON.stringify(entry) + '\\n');\n```\nUses `appendFileSync` (not `writeFileSync`). Directory created with `mkdirSync({ recursive: true })`.\n\nTests verify:\n- \"creates .codeharness/ directory if missing\" (line 50) — PASS\n- \"multiple sequential writes produce multiple lines\" (line 165) — writes 3 entries, gets 3 lines — PASS\n\n---\n\n## AC 5: version: 1 is the first field in serialized JSON\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// telemetry-writer.test.ts lines 118-123\nit('version is the first field in serialized JSON', async () => {\n  const ctx = makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir });\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(ctx);\n  const line = readTelemetryFile(tmpDir).trim();\n  expect(line.startsWith('{\"version\":1,')).toBe(true);\n});\n```\nTest passes. The `version` field is first in the TelemetryEntry interface (line 38) and `JSON.stringify` preserves insertion order.\n\n---\n\n## AC 6: readTelemetryForEpic filters by epicId correctly\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// telemetry-writer.test.ts lines 197-208\nit('filters entries by epicId', async () => {\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir, storyKey: '16-1-first' }));\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir, storyKey: '17-1-other' }));\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir, storyKey: '16-2-second' }));\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir, storyKey: '18-1-another' }));\n  const entries = readTelemetryForEpic('16', tmpDir);\n  expect(entries).toHaveLength(2);\n  expect(entries[0].storyKey).toBe('16-1-first');\n  expect(entries[1].storyKey).toBe('16-2-second');\n});\n```\nTest passes. Filters to only epic \"16\" entries, preserves insertion order.\n\n---\n\n## AC 7: null-task-registry.ts has real writeTelemetryEntry registered\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// src/lib/null-task-registry.ts line 13, 97\nimport { writeTelemetryEntry } from './telemetry-writer.js';\nregisterNullTask('telemetry', writeTelemetryEntry);\n```\nTest \"registered handler is the real writeTelemetryEntry function\" (line 266) verifies:\n```typescript\nconst handler = getNullTask('telemetry');\nexpect(handler).toBe(realWriteTelemetryEntry);\n```\nTest passes — reference equality confirms it is the real function, not a no-op.\n\n---\n\n## AC 8: Performance test (<10ms) exists and passes\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// telemetry-writer.test.ts lines 183-193\nit('completes in <10ms (performance, AC #8)', async () => {\n  mkdirSync(join(tmpDir, '.codeharness'), { recursive: true });\n  const ctx = makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir });\n  const start = performance.now();\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(ctx);\n  const elapsed = performance.now() - start;\n  expect(elapsed).toBeLessThan(10);\n});\n```\nTest passes. Full test suite duration: 12ms for 19 tests.\n\n---\n\n## AC 9: readTelemetryForEpic returns empty array when file doesn't exist\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// telemetry-writer.test.ts lines 210-213\nit('returns [] when file does not exist', () => {\n  const entries = readTelemetryForEpic('16', tmpDir);\n  expect(entries).toEqual([]);\n});\n```\nTest passes. Implementation at line 123: `if (!existsSync(filePath)) return [];`\n\n---\n\n## AC 10: Corrupted JSON line handling in readTelemetryForEpic\n\n**Verdict:** PASS\n\n**Evidence:**\n```typescript\n// telemetry-writer.test.ts lines 221-234\nit('skips corrupted JSON lines', async () => {\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir, storyKey: '16-1-first' }));\n  const filePath = join(tmpDir, '.codeharness', 'telemetry.jsonl');\n  appendFileSync(filePath, 'this is not valid json\\n');\n  appendFileSync(filePath, '{broken json\\n');\n  await writeTelemetryEntry(makeCtx({ projectDir: tmpDir, storyKey: '16-2-second' }));\n  const entries = readTelemetryForEpic('16', tmpDir);\n  expect(entries).toHaveLength(2);\n});\n```\nTest passes. Two corrupted lines are injected between valid entries; both are skipped silently.\n\nImplementation at lines 129-137 uses try/catch around `JSON.parse`, with `continue` on error.\n","numLines":216,"startLine":1,"totalLines":216}}}
